# =============================================================================
# LDIF Test Data — OUD test fixture (~15 users, 3 groups)
# Base DN: dc=oudtest,dc=example,dc=com
#
# Loaded on first volume init by the opendj-oud compose service.
# Designed to exercise the Oracle Unified Directory support phases
# (P1 generic CRUD, P3 changelog reuse of DseeChangelogStrategy,
# P4 nested-group resolution via isMemberOf) using OpenDJ as an
# Apache-2.0-licensed substitute for the OUD vendor image.
#
# OpenDJ is API-compatible with OUD (shared ODSEE/Sun ONE lineage)
# and serves the same isMemberOf operational attribute, ODSEE-style
# cn=changelog, and Sun-style root-DSE capability surface. Behavioural
# divergences from real Oracle OUD are documented in
# testdata/README-oud.md.
#
# Bind DN for the admin: cn=Directory Manager (OpenDJ default; set in
# the docker-compose env via ROOT_PASSWORD).
# =============================================================================

# ── Base DN — NOT included here ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# The openidentityplatform/opendj entrypoint creates the suffix entry
# `dc=oudtest,dc=example,dc=com` from the BASE_DN env var before the
# bootstrap-data import runs. Including a defensive `dn: dc=oudtest,...`
# ADD here causes the 5.x release's setup.sh to abort the LDIF on
# `Entry Already Exists (68)` — `--continueOnError` covers some errors
# but evidently not this one in this release. So this LDIF starts at
# the OU layer; the suffix entry is the container's job.

# ── Organisational units ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
dn: ou=people,dc=oudtest,dc=example,dc=com
objectClass: top
objectClass: organizationalUnit
ou: people

dn: ou=groups,dc=oudtest,dc=example,dc=com
objectClass: top
objectClass: organizationalUnit
ou: groups

# ── Users ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 15 inetOrgPerson entries split across three teams so the nested-group
# resolution test (P4) has interesting structure: an outer group
# `cn=allTechStaff` whose members are the two team-level groups
# (`cn=engineering`, `cn=design`); `isMemberOf` on a user should report
# both their direct team group and the outer aggregate.
#
# Every user's userPassword is their uid (e.g. alice.smith → alice.smith).
# Lengthen / scramble before exposing anywhere non-local.

dn: uid=alice.smith,ou=people,dc=oudtest,dc=example,dc=com
objectClass: top
objectClass: person
objectClass: organizationalPerson
objectClass: inetOrgPerson
uid: alice.smith
cn: Alice Smith
sn: Smith
givenName: Alice
mail: alice.smith@oudtest.example.com
userPassword: alice.smith
title: Staff Engineer
departmentNumber: ENG

